external_knowledge:
- "in the shadows" means the policy is not enabled (enabled = 0);
- "fleeting memory" signifies a retention period less than 30 days (retention_period < 30);
- "watched over by guardians with a long patience" indicates the policies have an archive cleanup policy enabled (archive_cleanup_policy = 1) and the cleanup days are more than 10 (archive_cleanup_days > 10).

sql:
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM connection_policies
WHERE override_global_policy = 0;

SELECT policy_type, description
FROM global_policies
WHERE enabled = 1 AND retention_period > 30;

SELECT connection_name, description
FROM connections
WHERE connection_id IN (SELECT connection_id FROM metadata);

SELECT *
FROM global_policies
ORDER BY retention_period DESC;

SELECT enabled
FROM global_policies
WHERE policy_id = 1;

external_knowledge:
- "Sails set to catch the wind" refers to active or enabled policies;
- "Automatic cleanup" metaphorically refers to the archive cleanup policy being enabled (archive_cleanup_policy = 1);
- "Navigating through the vast ocean of our connections database" refers to searching through the connections table to find those with the specified policy enabled.

Active policies refer to those that are enabled (Boolean flag enabled equals 1);
Cleanup and retention settings include global retention periods and channel database cleanup days;
Local cleanup times are specific to each connection and might override global settings if the override flag is set to true.

- "rivers" metaphorically refers to 'connection_name'.;
- "sea of data" metaphorically refers to the database or the final destination of the data.;
- "seeds" metaphorically refers to 'metadata entries' or 'metadata_id'.;
- "year of the cosmic clock" metaphorically refers to the calendar year 2022.;
- "average length of these seeds" refers to the average length of the metadata values. ;
- "over a dozen seeds" means more than 10 metadata entries. ;

sql:
SELECT * 
FROM metadata 
WHERE connection_id IN (
    SELECT connection_id 
    FROM connections 
    WHERE updated_at = (
        SELECT MAX(updated_at) 
        FROM connections
    )
);

external_knowledge:
- Unique cleanup and timestamping policies refer to conditions where the connection overrides the global policy, has an active archive cleanup policy with longer retention than set locally, and uses a non-standard timestamp format;
- The standard timestamp format is 'YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS';
- Global settings are the default policies applied to all connections unless overridden.
